# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bqp-class
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bqp-class/bqp] In computational complexity theory, **bounded-error quantum polynomial time** (**BQP**) is the class of decision problems solvable by a quantum computer in polynomial time, with an error probability of at most 1/3 for all instances.
[src:bqp-class/bqp] It is the quantum analogue to the complexity class **BPP**.
[src:bqp-class/bqp] A decision problem is a member of **BQP** if there exists a quantum algorithm (an algorithm that runs on a quantum computer) that solves the decision problem with high probability and is guaranteed to run in polynomial time.
[src:bqp-class/bqp] A run of the algorithm will correctly solve the decision problem with a probability of at least 2/3.
[src:bqp-class/bqp] Alternatively, one can define **BQP** in terms of quantum Turing machines.
[src:bqp-class/bqp] A language *L* is in **BQP** if and only if there exists a polynomial quantum Turing machine that accepts *L* with an error probability of at most 1/3 for all instances.
[src:bqp-class/bqp] Similarly to other "bounded error" probabilistic classes, the choice of 1/3 in the definition is arbitrary.
[src:bqp-class/bqp] We can run the algorithm a constant number of times and take a majority vote to achieve any desired probability of correctness less than 1, using the Chernoff bound.
[src:bqp-class/bqp] The complexity class is unchanged by allowing error as high as 1/2 − *n*−*c* on the one hand, or requiring error as small as 2−*nc* on the other hand, where *c* is any positive constant, and *n* is the length of input.
[src:bqp-class/bqp] BQP is defined for quantum computers; the corresponding complexity class for classical computers (or more formally for probabilistic Turing machines) is **BPP**.
[src:bqp-class/bqp] Just like **P** and **BPP**, **BQP** is low for itself, which means BQPBQP = BQP.
[src:bqp-class/bqp] Informally, this is true because polynomial time algorithms are closed under composition.
[src:bqp-class/bqp] If a polynomial time algorithm calls polynomial time algorithms as subroutines, the resulting algorithm is still polynomial time.
[src:bqp-class/bqp] As the problem of ⁠ ${\mathsf {P}}\ {\stackrel {?}{=}}\ {\mathsf {PSPACE}}$ ⁠ has not yet been solved, the proof of inequality between **BQP** and classes mentioned above is supposed to be difficult.
[src:bqp-class/bqp] The relation between **BQP** and **NP** is not known.
[src:bqp-class/bqp] In May 2018, computer scientists Ran Raz of Princeton University and Avishay Tal of Stanford University published a paper which showed that, relative to an oracle, BQP was not contained in PH.
[src:bqp-class/bqp] It can be proven that there exists an oracle A such that ${\mathsf {BQP}}^{\mathrm {A} }\nsubseteq {\mathsf {PH}}^{\mathrm {A} }$ .
[src:bqp-class/bqp] In an extremely informal sense, this can be thought of as giving PH and BQP an identical, but additional, capability and verifying that BQP with the oracle (BQPA) can do things PHA cannot.
[src:bqp-class/bqp] While an oracle separation has been proven, the fact that BQP is not contained in PH has not been proven.
[src:bqp-class/bqp] An oracle separation does not prove whether or not complexity classes are the same.
[src:bqp-class/bqp] The oracle separation gives intuition that BQP may not be contained in PH.
[src:bqp-class/bqp] It has been suspected for many years that Fourier Sampling is a problem that exists within BQP, but not within the polynomial hierarchy.
[src:bqp-class/bqp] Recent conjectures have provided evidence that a similar problem, Fourier Checking, also exists in the class BQP without being contained in the polynomial hierarchy.
[src:bqp-class/bqp] This conjecture is especially notable because it suggests that problems existing in BQP could be classified as harder than NP-Complete problems.
[src:bqp-class/bqp] Paired with the fact that many practical BQP problems are suspected to exist outside of P (it is suspected and not verified because there is no proof that P ≠ NP), this illustrates the potential power of quantum computing in relation to classical computing.
[src:bqp-class/bqp] Adding postselection to **BQP** results in the complexity class **PostBQP** which is equal to **PP**.
[src:bqp-class/bqp] Promise-BQP is the class of promise problems that can be solved by a uniform family of quantum circuits (i.e., within BQP).
[src:bqp-class/bqp] Completeness proofs focus on this version of BQP.
[src:bqp-class/bqp] Similar to the notion of NP-completeness and other complete problems, we can define a complete problem as a problem that is in Promise-BQP and that every other problem in Promise-BQP reduces to it in polynomial time.
[src:bqp-class/bqp] The APPROX-QCIRCUIT-PROB problem is complete for efficient quantum computation, and the version presented below is complete for the Promise-BQP complexity class (and not for the total BQP complexity class, for which no complete problems are known).
[src:bqp-class/bqp] APPROX-QCIRCUIT-PROB's completeness makes it useful for proofs showing the relationships between other complexity classes and BQP.
[src:bqp-class/bqp] Here, there is a promise on the inputs as the problem does not specify the behavior if an instance is not covered by these two cases.
[src:bqp-class/bqp] For any $L\in {\mathsf {BQP}}$ , there exists family of quantum circuits $\{Q_{n}\colon n\in \mathbb {N} \}$ such that for all $n\in \mathbb {N}$ , a state $|x\rangle$ of n qubits, if $x\in L,Pr(Q_{n}(|x\rangle )=1)\geq 2/3$ ; else if $x\notin L,Pr(Q_{n}(|x\rangle )=0)\geq 2/3$ .
[src:bqp-class/bqp] Fix an input $|x\rangle$ of n qubits, and the corresponding quantum circuit $Q_{n}$ .
[src:bqp-class/bqp] We can first construct a circuit $C_{x}$ such that $C_{x}|0\rangle ^{\otimes n}=|x\rangle$ .
[src:bqp-class/bqp] This can be done easily by hardwiring $|x\rangle$ and apply a sequence of CNOT gates to flip the qubits.
[src:bqp-class/bqp] Then we can combine two circuits to get $C'=Q_{n}C_{x}$ , and now $C'|0\rangle ^{\otimes n}=Q_{n}|x\rangle$ .
[src:bqp-class/bqp] And finally, necessarily the results of $Q_{n}$ is obtained by measuring several qubits and apply some (classical) logic gates to them.
[src:bqp-class/bqp] We can always defer the measurement and reroute the circuits so that by measuring the first qubit of $C'|0\rangle ^{\otimes n}=Q_{n}|x\rangle$ , we get the output.
[src:bqp-class/bqp] This will be our circuit C, and we decide the membership of $x\in L$ by running $A(C)$ with $\alpha =2/3,\beta =1/3$ .
[src:bqp-class/bqp] By definition of BQP, we will either fall into the first case (acceptance), or the second case (rejection), so $L\in {\mathsf {BQP}}$ reduces to APPROX-QCIRCUIT-PROB.
[src:bqp-class/bqp] To show that ${\mathsf {BQP}}\subseteq {\mathsf {EXP}}$ , it suffices to show that APPROX-QCIRCUIT-PROB is in EXP since APPROX-QCIRCUIT-PROB is BQP-complete.
[src:bqp-class/bqp] Since we have exponential power, given a quantum circuit C, we can use classical computer to stimulate each gate in C to get the final state.
[src:bqp-class/bqp] More formally, let C be a polynomial sized quantum circuit on n qubits and m gates, where m is polynomial in n.
[src:bqp-class/bqp] Let $|\psi _{0}\rangle =|0\rangle ^{\otimes n}$ and $|\psi _{i}\rangle$ be the state after the i-th gate in the circuit is applied to $|\psi _{i-1}\rangle$ .
[src:bqp-class/bqp] Each state $|\psi _{i}\rangle$ can be represented in a classical computer as a unit vector in $\mathbb {C} ^{2^{n}}$ .
[src:bqp-class/bqp] Furthermore, each gate can be represented by a matrix in $\mathbb {C} ^{2^{n}\times 2^{n}}$ .
[src:bqp-class/bqp] Hence, the final state $|\psi _{m}\rangle$ can be computed in $O(m\cdot 2^{2n})$ time, and therefore all together, we have an $2^{O(n)}$ time algorithm for calculating the final state, and thus the probability that the first qubit is measured to be one.
[src:bqp-class/bqp] This implies that ${\text{APPROX-QCIRCUIT-PROB}}\in {\mathsf {EXP}}$ .
[src:bqp-class/bqp] Note that this algorithm also requires $2^{O(n)}$ space to store the vectors and the matrices.
[src:bqp-class/bqp] We will show in the following section that we can improve upon the space complexity.
[src:bqp-class/bqp] Sum of histories is a technique introduced by physicist Richard Feynman for path integral formulation.
[src:bqp-class/bqp] APPROX-QCIRCUIT-PROB can be formulated in the sum of histories technique to show that ${\mathsf {BQP}}\subseteq {\mathsf {PSPACE}}$ .
[src:bqp-class/bqp] Consider a quantum circuit C, which consists of t gates, $g_{1},g_{2},\cdots ,g_{m}$ , where each $g_{j}$ comes from a universal gate set and acts on at most two qubits.
[src:bqp-class/bqp] To understand what the sum of histories is, we visualize the evolution of a quantum state given a quantum circuit as a tree.
[src:bqp-class/bqp] The root is the input $|0\rangle ^{\otimes n}$ , and each node in the tree has $2^{n}$ children, each representing a state in $\mathbb {C} ^{n}$ .
[src:bqp-class/bqp] The weight on a tree edge from a node in j-th level representing a state $|x\rangle$ to a node in $j+1$ -th level representing a state $|y\rangle$ is $\langle y|g_{j+1}|x\rangle$ , the amplitude of $|y\rangle$ after applying $g_{j+1}$ on $|x\rangle$ .
[src:bqp-class/bqp] The transition amplitude of a root-to-leaf path is the product of all the weights on the edges along the path.
[src:bqp-class/bqp] To get the probability of the final state being $|\psi \rangle$ , we sum up the amplitudes of all root-to-leave paths that ends at a node representing $|\psi \rangle$ .
[src:bqp-class/bqp] More formally, for the quantum circuit C, its sum over histories tree is a tree of depth m, with one level for each gate $g_{i}$ in addition to the root, and with branching factor $2^{n}$ .
[src:bqp-class/bqp] Each gate $g_{j}$ can be decomposed into $g_{j}=I\otimes {\tilde {g}}_{j}$ for some unitary operator ${\tilde {g}}_{j}$ acting on two qubits, which without loss of generality can be taken to be the first two.
[src:bqp-class/bqp] Since m is polynomial in n, the transition amplitude of the history can be computed in polynomial time.
[src:bqp-class/bqp] The result comes directly by inserting $I=\sum _{x\in \{0,1\}^{n}}|x\rangle \langle x|$ between $g_{1},g_{2}$ , and $g_{2},g_{3}$ , and so on, and then expand out the equation.
[src:bqp-class/bqp] Notice in the sum over histories algorithm to compute some amplitude $\alpha _{x}$ , only one history is stored at any point in the computation.
[src:bqp-class/bqp] Hence, the sum over histories algorithm uses $O(nm)$ space to compute $\alpha _{x}$ for any x since $O(nm)$ bits are needed to store the histories in addition to some workspace variables.
[src:bqp-class/bqp] Therefore, in polynomial space, we may compute $\sum _{x}|\alpha _{x}|^{2}$ over all x with the first qubit being 1, which is the probability that the first qubit is measured to be 1 by the end of the circuit.
[src:bqp-class/bqp] Notice that compared with the simulation given for the proof that ${\mathsf {BQP}}\subseteq {\mathsf {EXP}}$ , our algorithm here takes far less space but far more time instead.
[src:bqp-class/bqp] In fact it takes $O(m\cdot 2^{mn})$ time to calculate a single amplitude!
[src:bqp-class/bqp] A similar sum-over-histories argument can be used to show that ${\mathsf {BQP}}\subseteq {\mathsf {PP}}$ .
[src:bqp-class/bqp] We know ${\mathsf {P}}\subseteq {\mathsf {BQP}}$ , since every classical circuit can be simulated by a quantum circuit.
[src:bqp-class/bqp] It is conjectured that BQP solves hard problems outside of P, specifically, problems in NP.
[src:bqp-class/bqp] The claim is indefinite because we don't know if P=NP, so we don't know if those problems are actually in P.
[src:bqp-class/deutsch-jozsa-algorithm] The **Deutsch–Jozsa algorithm** is a deterministic quantum algorithm proposed by David Deutsch and Richard Jozsa in 1992 with improvements by Richard Cleve, Artur Ekert, Chiara Macchiavello, and Michele Mosca in 1998.
[src:bqp-class/deutsch-jozsa-algorithm] Although of little practical use, it is one of the first examples of a quantum algorithm that is exponentially faster than any possible deterministic classical algorithm.
[src:bqp-class/deutsch-jozsa-algorithm] The Deutsch–Jozsa problem is specifically designed to be easy for a quantum algorithm and hard for any deterministic classical algorithm.
[src:bqp-class/deutsch-jozsa-algorithm] It is a black box problem that can be solved efficiently by a quantum computer with no error, whereas a deterministic classical computer would need an exponential number of queries to the black box to solve the problem.
[src:bqp-class/deutsch-jozsa-algorithm] More formally, it yields an oracle relative to which **EQP**, the class of problems that can be solved exactly in polynomial time on a quantum computer, and **P** are different.
[src:bqp-class/deutsch-jozsa-algorithm] Since the problem is easy to solve on a probabilistic classical computer, it does not yield an oracle separation with **BPP**, the class of problems that can be solved with bounded error in polynomial time on a probabilistic classical computer.
[src:bqp-class/deutsch-jozsa-algorithm] Simon's problem is an example of a problem that yields an oracle separation between **BQP** and **BPP**.
[src:bqp-class/deutsch-jozsa-algorithm] The function takes n-bit binary values as input and produces either a 0 or a 1 as output for each such value.
[src:bqp-class/deutsch-jozsa-algorithm] We are promised that the function is either constant (0 on all inputs or 1 on all inputs) or *balanced* (1 for exactly half of the input domain and 0 for the other half).
[src:bqp-class/deutsch-jozsa-algorithm] The task then is to determine if f is constant or balanced by using the oracle.
[src:bqp-class/deutsch-jozsa-algorithm] For a conventional deterministic algorithm where n is the number of bits, $2^{n-1}+1$ evaluations of f will be required in the worst case.
[src:bqp-class/deutsch-jozsa-algorithm] To prove that f is constant, just over half the set of inputs must be evaluated and their outputs found to be identical (because the function is guaranteed to be either balanced or constant, not somewhere in between).
[src:bqp-class/deutsch-jozsa-algorithm] The best case occurs where the function is balanced and the first two output values are different.
[src:bqp-class/deutsch-jozsa-algorithm] For a conventional randomized algorithm, a constant k evaluations of the function suffices to produce the correct answer with a high probability (failing with probability $\epsilon \leq 1/2^{k}$ with $k\geq 1$ ).
[src:bqp-class/deutsch-jozsa-algorithm] However, $k=2^{n-1}+1$ evaluations are still required if we want an answer that has no possibility of error.
[src:bqp-class/deutsch-jozsa-algorithm] The Deutsch-Jozsa quantum algorithm produces an answer that is always correct with a single evaluation of f .
[src:bqp-class/deutsch-jozsa-algorithm] The Deutsch–Jozsa algorithm generalizes earlier (1985) work by David Deutsch, which provided a solution for the simple case where $n=1$ .
[src:bqp-class/deutsch-jozsa-algorithm] Specifically, finding out if a given Boolean function whose input is one bit, $f:\{0,1\}\to \{0,1\}$ , is constant.
[src:bqp-class/deutsch-jozsa-algorithm] The algorithm, as Deutsch had originally proposed it, was not deterministic.
[src:bqp-class/deutsch-jozsa-algorithm] The algorithm was successful with a probability of one half.
[src:bqp-class/deutsch-jozsa-algorithm] In 1992, Deutsch and Jozsa produced a deterministic algorithm which was generalized to a function which takes n bits for its input.
[src:bqp-class/deutsch-jozsa-algorithm] Unlike Deutsch's algorithm, this algorithm required two function evaluations instead of only one.
[src:bqp-class/deutsch-jozsa-algorithm] Further improvements to the Deutsch–Jozsa algorithm were made by Cleve et al., resulting in an algorithm that is both deterministic and requires only a single query of f .
[src:bqp-class/deutsch-jozsa-algorithm] This algorithm is still referred to as Deutsch–Jozsa algorithm in honour of the groundbreaking techniques they employed.
[src:bqp-class/deutsch-jozsa-algorithm] For the Deutsch–Jozsa algorithm to work, the oracle computing $f(x)$ from x must be a quantum oracle which does not decohere x .
[src:bqp-class/deutsch-jozsa-algorithm] In its computation, it cannot make a copy of x , because that would violate the no cloning theorem.
[src:bqp-class/deutsch-jozsa-algorithm] The point of view of the Deutsch-Jozsa algorithm of f as an oracle means that it does not matter what the oracle does, since it just has to perform its promised transformation.
[src:bqp-class/deutsch-jozsa-algorithm] The algorithm begins with the $n+1$ bit state $|0\rangle ^{\otimes n}|1\rangle$ .
[src:bqp-class/deutsch-jozsa-algorithm] That is, the first n bits are each in the state $|0\rangle$ and the final bit is $|1\rangle$ .
[src:bqp-class/deutsch-jozsa-algorithm] where x runs over all n -bit strings, which each may be represented by a number from 0 to $2^{n}-1$ .
[src:bqp-class/deutsch-jozsa-algorithm] We have the function f implemented as a quantum oracle.
[src:bqp-class/deutsch-jozsa-algorithm] The oracle maps its input state $|x\rangle |y\rangle$ to $|x\rangle |y\oplus f(x)\rangle$ , where $\oplus$ denotes addition modulo 2.
[src:bqp-class/deutsch-jozsa-algorithm] Next, we will have each qubit go through a Hadamard gate.
[src:bqp-class/deutsch-jozsa-algorithm] which evaluates to 1 if $f(x)$ is constant (constructive interference) and 0 if $f(x)$ is balanced (destructive interference).
[src:bqp-class/deutsch-jozsa-algorithm] In other words, the final measurement will be $|0\rangle ^{\otimes n}$ (all zeros) if and only if $f(x)$ is constant and will yield some other state if $f(x)$ is balanced.
[src:bqp-class/deutsch-jozsa-algorithm] Deutsch's algorithm is a special case of the general Deutsch–Jozsa algorithm where n = 1, so that $f\colon \{0,1\}\rightarrow \{0,1\}$ .
[src:bqp-class/deutsch-jozsa-algorithm] We need to check the condition $f(0)=f(1)$ .
[src:bqp-class/deutsch-jozsa-algorithm] It is equivalent to check $f(0)\oplus f(1)$ (where $\oplus$ is addition modulo 2, which can also be viewed as a quantum XOR gate implemented as a Controlled NOT gate), if zero, then f is constant, otherwise f is not constant.
[src:bqp-class/deutsch-jozsa-algorithm] We begin with the two-qubit state $|0\rangle |1\rangle$ and apply a Hadamard gate to each qubit.
[src:bqp-class/deutsch-jozsa-algorithm] We are given a quantum implementation of the function f that maps $|x\rangle |y\rangle$ to $|x\rangle |f(x)\oplus y\rangle$ .
[src:bqp-class/deutsch-jozsa-algorithm] $f(0)\oplus f(1)=0$ if and only if we measure $|0\rangle$ and $f(0)\oplus f(1)=1$ if and only if we measure $|1\rangle$ .
[src:bqp-class/deutsch-jozsa-algorithm] So with certainty we know whether $f(x)$ is constant or balanced.
[src:bqp-class/deutsch-jozsa-algorithm] The quantum circuit shown here is from a simple example of how the Deutsch–Jozsa algorithm can be implemented in Python using Qiskit, an open-source quantum computing software development framework by IBM.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] It was devised by an Indian-American computer scientist Lov Grover in 1996.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] The analogous problem in classical computation would have a query complexity $O(N)$ (i.e., the function would have to be evaluated $O(N)$ times: there is no better approach than trying out all input values one after the other, which, on average, takes $N/2$ steps).
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] Bennett, Ethan Bernstein, Gilles Brassard, and Umesh Vazirani proved that any quantum solution to the problem needs to evaluate the function $\Omega ({\sqrt {N}})$ times, so Grover's algorithm is asymptotically optimal.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] Unlike other quantum algorithms, which may provide exponential speedup over their classical counterparts, Grover's algorithm provides only a quadratic speedup.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] However, even quadratic speedup is considerable when N is large, and Grover's algorithm can be applied to speed up broad classes of algorithms.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] Grover's algorithm could brute-force a 128-bit symmetric cryptographic key in roughly 264 iterations, or a 256-bit key in roughly 2128 iterations.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] It may not be the case that Grover's algorithm poses a significantly increased risk to encryption over existing classical algorithms, however.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] Grover's algorithm, along with variants like amplitude amplification, can be used to speed up a broad range of algorithms.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] In particular, algorithms for NP-complete problems which contain exhaustive search as a subroutine can be sped up by Grover's algorithm.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] The current theoretical best algorithm, in terms of worst-case complexity, for 3SAT is one such example.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] Generic constraint satisfaction problems also see quadratic speedups with Grover.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] These algorithms do not require that the input be given in the form of an oracle, since Grover's algorithm is being applied with an explicit function, e.g. the function checking that a set of bits satisfies a 3SAT instance.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] However, it is unclear whether Grover's algorithm could speed up best practical algorithms for these problems.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] Grover's algorithm can also give provable speedups for black-box problems in quantum query complexity, including element distinctness and the collision problem (solved with the Brassard–Høyer–Tapp algorithm).
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] In these types of problems, one treats the oracle function *f* as a database, and the goal is to use the quantum query to this function as few times as possible.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] Grover's algorithm essentially solves the task of *function inversion*.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] Roughly speaking, if we have a function $y=f(x)$ that can be evaluated on a quantum computer, Grover's algorithm allows us to calculate x when given y .
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] Consequently, Grover's algorithm gives broad asymptotic speed-ups to many kinds of brute-force attacks on symmetric-key cryptography, including collision attacks and pre-image attacks.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] However, this may not necessarily be the most efficient algorithm since, for example, the Pollard's rho algorithm is able to find a collision in SHA-2 more efficiently than Grover's algorithm.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] Grover's original paper described the algorithm as a database search algorithm, and this description is still common.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] The database in this analogy is a table of all of the function's outputs, indexed by the corresponding input.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] However, this database is not represented explicitly.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] Instead, an oracle is invoked to evaluate an item by its index.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] Reading a full database item by item and converting it into such a representation may take a lot longer than Grover's search.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] To account for such effects, Grover's algorithm can be viewed as solving an equation or satisfying a constraint.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] In such applications, the oracle is a way to check the constraint and is not related to the search algorithm.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] This separation usually prevents algorithmic optimizations, whereas conventional search algorithms often rely on such optimizations and avoid exhaustive search.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] Fortunately, fast Grover's oracle implementation is possible for many constraint satisfaction and optimization problems.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] The major barrier to instantiating a speedup from Grover's algorithm is that the quadratic speedup achieved is too modest to overcome the large overhead of near-term quantum computers.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] However, later generations of fault-tolerant quantum computers with better hardware performance may be able to realize these speedups for practical instances of data.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] As input for Grover's algorithm, suppose we have a function $f\colon \{0,1,\ldots ,N-1\}\to \{0,1\}$ .
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] In the "unstructured database" analogy, the domain represent indices to a database, and $f(x)=1$ if the data that x points to satisfies the search criterion.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] We additionally assume that only one index satisfies $f(x)=1$ , and we call this index $\omega$ .
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] This uses the N -dimensional state space ${\mathcal {H}}$ , which is supplied by a register with $n=\lceil \log _{2}N\rceil$ qubits.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] Grover's algorithm outputs $\omega$ with probability at least $1/2$ using $O({\sqrt {N}})$ applications of $U_{\omega }$ .
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] This probability can be made arbitrarily large by running Grover's algorithm multiple times.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] If one runs Grover's algorithm until $\omega$ is found, the expected number of applications is still $O({\sqrt {N}})$ , since it will only be run twice on average.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] This section compares the above oracle $U_{\omega }$ with an oracle $U_{f}$ .
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] $U_{\omega }$ is different from the standard quantum oracle for a function f .
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] This standard oracle, denoted here as $U_{f}$ , uses an ancillary qubit system.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] These oracles are typically realized using uncomputation.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] So, Grover's algorithm can be run regardless of which oracle is given.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] If $U_{f}$ is given, then we must maintain an additional qubit in the state $|-\rangle$ and apply $U_{f}$ in place of $U_{\omega }$ .
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] Measure the resulting quantum state in the computational basis.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] For the correctly chosen value of r , the output will be $|\omega \rangle$ with probability approaching 1 for *N* ≫ 1.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] Analysis shows that this eventual value for $r(N)$ satisfies $r(N)\leq {\Big \lceil }{\frac {\pi }{4}}{\sqrt {N}}{\Big \rceil }$ .
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] Implementing the steps for this algorithm can be done using a number of gates linear in the number of qubits.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] Thus, the gate complexity of this algorithm is $O(\log(N)r(N))$ , or $O(\log(N))$ per iteration.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] There is a geometric interpretation of Grover's algorithm, following from the observation that the quantum state of Grover's algorithm stays in a two-dimensional subspace after each step.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] Consider the plane spanned by $|s\rangle$ and $|\omega \rangle$ ; equivalently, the plane spanned by $|\omega \rangle$ and the perpendicular ket $\textstyle |s'\rangle ={\frac {1}{\sqrt {N-1}}}\sum _{x\neq \omega }|x\rangle$ .
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] Grover's algorithm begins with the initial ket $|s\rangle$ , which lies in the subspace.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] The operator $U_{\omega }$ is a reflection at the hyperplane orthogonal to $|\omega \rangle$ for vectors in the plane spanned by $|s'\rangle$ and $|\omega \rangle$ , i.e. it acts as a reflection across $|s'\rangle$ .
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] The operator $U_{s}=2|s\rangle \langle s|-I$ is a reflection through $|s\rangle$ .
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] Both operators $U_{s}$ and $U_{\omega }$ take states in the plane spanned by $|s'\rangle$ and $|\omega \rangle$ to states in the plane.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] Therefore, Grover's algorithm stays in this plane for the entire algorithm.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] It is straightforward to check that the operator $U_{s}U_{\omega }$ of each Grover iteration step rotates the state vector by an angle of $\theta =2\arcsin {\tfrac {1}{\sqrt {N}}}$ .
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] So, with enough iterations, one can rotate from the initial state $|s\rangle$ to the desired output state $|\omega \rangle$ .
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] We need to stop when the state vector passes close to $|\omega \rangle$ ; after this, subsequent iterations rotate the state vector *away* from $|\omega \rangle$ , reducing the probability of obtaining the correct answer.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] where *r* is the (integer) number of Grover iterations.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] The earliest time that we get a near-optimal measurement is therefore $r\approx \pi {\sqrt {N}}/4$ .
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] To complete the algebraic analysis, we need to find out what happens when we repeatedly apply $U_{s}U_{\omega }$ .
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] A natural way to do this is by eigenvalue analysis of a matrix.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] Notice that during the entire computation, the state of the algorithm is a linear combination of s and $\omega$ .
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] This matrix happens to have a very convenient Jordan form.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] Alternatively, one might reasonably imagine that a near-optimal time to distinguish would be when the angles 2*rt* and −2*rt* are as far apart as possible, which corresponds to $2rt\approx \pi /2$ , or $r=\pi /4t=\pi /4\arcsin(1/{\sqrt {N}})\approx \pi {\sqrt {N}}/4$ .
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] A short calculation now shows that the observation yields the correct answer *ω* with error $O\left({\frac {1}{N}}\right)$ .
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] If, instead of 1 matching entry, there are *k* matching entries, the same algorithm works, but the number of iterations must be ${\textstyle {\frac {\pi }{4}}{\sqrt {\frac {N}{k}}}}$ instead of ${\textstyle {\frac {\pi }{4}}{\sqrt {N}}}$ .
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] There are several ways to handle the case if *k* is unknown.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] A simple solution performs optimally up to a constant factor: run Grover's algorithm repeatedly for increasingly small values of *k*, e.g., taking *k* = *N*, *N*/2, *N*/4, ..., and so on, taking $k=N/2^{t}$ for iteration *t* until a matching entry is found.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] With sufficiently high probability, a marked entry will be found by iteration $t=\log _{2}(N/k)+c$ for some constant *c*.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] Another approach if *k* is unknown is to derive it via the quantum counting algorithm prior.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] If $k=N/2$ (or the traditional one marked state Grover's Algorithm if run with $N=2$ ), the algorithm will provide no amplification.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] If $k>N/2$ , increasing *k* will begin to increase the number of iterations necessary to obtain a solution.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] On the other hand, if $k\geq N/2$ , a classical running of the checking oracle on a single random choice of input will more likely than not give a correct solution.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] A version of this algorithm is used in order to solve the collision problem.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] A modification of Grover's algorithm called quantum partial search was described by Grover and Radhakrishnan in 2004.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] In partial search, one is not interested in finding the exact address of the target item, only the first few digits of the address.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] Equivalently, we can think of "chunking" the search space into blocks, and then asking "in which block is the target item?".
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] In many applications, such a search yields enough information if the target address contains the information wanted.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] For instance, to use the example given by L.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] Grover, if one has a list of students organized by class rank, we may only be interested in whether a student is in the lower 25%, 25–50%, 50–75% or 75–100% percentile.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] To describe partial search, we consider a database separated into K blocks, each of size $b=N/K$ .
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] Consider the approach we would take classically – we pick one block at random, and then perform a normal search through the rest of the blocks (in set theory language, the complement).
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] If we do not find the target, then we know it is in the block we did not search.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] The average number of iterations drops from $N/2$ to $(N-b)/2$ .
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] Grover's algorithm requires ${\textstyle {\frac {\pi }{4}}{\sqrt {N}}}$ iterations.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] Partial search will be faster by a numerical factor that depends on the number of blocks K .
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] Partial search uses $n_{1}$ global iterations and $n_{2}$ local iterations.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] The global Grover operator is designated $G_{1}$ and the local Grover operator is designated $G_{2}$ .
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] The global Grover operator acts on the blocks.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] Perform $j_{2}$ local Grover iterations.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] A local Grover iteration is a direct sum of Grover iterations over each block.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] The optimal values of $j_{1}$ and $j_{2}$ are discussed in the paper by Grover and Radhakrishnan.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] One might also wonder what happens if one applies successive partial searches at different levels of "resolution".
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] This idea was studied in detail by Vladimir Korepin and Xu, who called it binary quantum search.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] They proved that it is not in fact any faster than performing a single partial search.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] Grover's algorithm is optimal up to sub-constant factors.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] That is, any algorithm that accesses the database only by using the operator *Uω* must apply *Uω* at least a $1-o(1)$ fraction as many times as Grover's algorithm.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] The extension of Grover's algorithm to *k* matching entries, π(*N*/*k*)1/2/4, is also optimal.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] This result is important in understanding the limits of quantum computation.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] If the Grover's search problem was solvable with logc *N* applications of *Uω*, that would imply that NP is contained in BQP, by transforming problems in NP into Grover-type search problems.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] The optimality of Grover's algorithm suggests that quantum computers cannot solve NP-Complete problems in polynomial time, and thus NP is not contained in BQP.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] It has been shown that a class of non-local hidden variable quantum computers could implement a search of an N -item database in at most $O({\sqrt[{3}]{N}})$ steps.
[src:bqp-class/grover-s-algorithm] This is faster than the $O({\sqrt {N}})$ steps taken by Grover's algorithm.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] In quantum information theory, a **quantum circuit** is a model for quantum computation, similar to classical circuits, in which a computation is a sequence of quantum gates, measurements, initializations of qubits to known values, and possibly other actions.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] The minimum set of actions that a circuit needs to be able to perform on the qubits to enable quantum computation is known as DiVincenzo's criteria.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] Circuits are written such that the horizontal axis is time, starting at the left hand side and ending at the right.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] Horizontal lines are qubits, doubled lines represent classical bits.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] The items that are connected by these lines are operations performed on the qubits, such as measurements or gates.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] These lines define the sequence of events, and are usually not physical cables.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] The graphical depiction of quantum circuit elements is described using a variant of the Penrose graphical notation.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] Richard Feynman used an early version of the quantum circuit notation in 1986.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] Most elementary logic gates of a classical computer are not reversible.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] Thus, for instance, for an AND gate one cannot always recover the two input bits from the output bit; for example, if the output bit is 0, we cannot tell from this whether the input bits are 01 or 10 or 00.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] However, reversible gates in classical computers are easily constructed for bit strings of any length; moreover, these are actually of practical interest, since irreversible gates must always increase physical entropy.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] A reversible gate is a reversible function on *n*-bit data that returns *n*-bit data, where an *n*-bit data is a string of bits *x*1,*x*2, ...,*x**n* of length *n*.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] The set of *n*-bit data is the space {0,1}*n*, which consists of 2*n* strings of 0's and 1's.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] More precisely: an *n*-bit reversible gate is a bijective mapping *f* from the set {0,1}*n* of *n*-bit data onto itself.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] An example of such a reversible gate *f* is a mapping that applies a fixed permutation to its inputs.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] For reasons of practical engineering, one typically studies gates only for small values of *n*, e.g.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] These gates can be easily described by tables.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] The quantum logic gates are reversible unitary transformations on at least one qubit.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] Multiple qubits taken together are referred to as quantum registers.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] To define quantum gates, we first need to specify the quantum replacement of an *n*-bit datum.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] This is by definition the space of complex-valued functions on {0,1}*n* and is naturally an inner product space. $\ell ^{2}$ means the function is a square-integrable function.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] This space can also be regarded as consisting of linear combinations, or superpositions, of classical bit strings.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] Note that *H*QB(*n*) is a vector space over the complex numbers of dimension 2*n*.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] The elements of this vector space are the possible state-vectors of *n*-qubit quantum registers.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] is a special *n*-qubit register corresponding to the function which maps this classical bit string to 1 and maps all other bit strings to 0; these 2*n* special *n*-qubit registers are called *computational basis states*.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] All *n*-qubit registers are complex linear combinations of these computational basis states.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] Quantum logic gates, in contrast to classical logic gates, are always reversible.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] One requires a special kind of reversible function, namely a unitary mapping, that is, a linear transformation of a complex inner product space that preserves the Hermitian inner product.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] An *n*-qubit (reversible) quantum gate is a unitary mapping *U* from the space *H*QB(*n*) of *n*-qubit registers onto itself.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] Typically, we are only interested in gates for small values of *n*.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] Note that *W**f* permutes the computational basis states.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] Of particular importance is the controlled NOT gate (also called CNOT gate) *W*CNOT defined on a quantized 2 qubit.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] Other examples of quantum logic gates derived from classical ones are the Toffoli gate and the Fredkin gate.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] However, the Hilbert-space structure of the qubits permits many quantum gates that are not induced by classical ones.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] Again, we consider first *reversible* classical computation.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] Conceptually, there is no difference between a reversible *n*-bit circuit and a reversible *n*-bit logic gate: either one is just an invertible function on the space of *n* bit data.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] However, as mentioned in the previous section, for engineering reasons we would like to have a small number of simple reversible gates, that can be put together to assemble any reversible circuit.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] To explain this assembly process, suppose we have a reversible *n*-bit gate *f* and a reversible *m*-bit gate *g*.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] Putting them together means producing a new circuit by connecting some set of *k* outputs of *f* to some set of *k* inputs of *g* as in the figure below.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] The resulting circuit is also reversible and operates on *n*+*m*−*k* bits.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] We will refer to this scheme as a *classical assemblage* (This concept corresponds to a technical definition in Kitaev's pioneering paper cited below).
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] In composing these reversible machines, it is important to ensure that the intermediate machines are also reversible.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] This condition assures that *intermediate* "garbage" is not created (the net physical effect would be to increase entropy, which is one of the motivations for going through this exercise).
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] Note that each horizontal line on the above picture represents either 0 or 1, not these probabilities.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] Since quantum computations are reversible, at each 'step' the number of lines must be the same number of input lines.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] Also, each input combination must be mapped to a single combination at each 'step'.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] This means that each intermediate combination in a quantum circuit is a bijective function of the input.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] Now it is possible to show that the Toffoli gate is a universal gate.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] Notice that the result always has a string of *m* zeros as the ancilla bits.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] No "rubbish" is ever produced, and so this computation is indeed one that, in a physical sense, generates no entropy.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] This issue is carefully discussed in Kitaev's article.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] More generally, any function *f* (bijective or not) can be simulated by a circuit of Toffoli gates.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] Obviously, if the mapping fails to be injective, at some point in the simulation (for example as the last step) some "garbage" has to be produced.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] For quantum circuits a similar composition of qubit gates can be defined.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] That is, associated to any *classical assemblage* as above, we can produce a reversible quantum circuit when in place of *f* we have an *n*-qubit gate *U* and in place of *g* we have an *m*-qubit gate *W*.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] The fact that connecting gates this way gives rise to a unitary mapping on *n*+*m*−*k* qubit space is easy to check.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] In a real quantum computer the physical connection between the gates is a major engineering challenge, since it is one of the places where decoherence may occur.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] There are also universality theorems for certain sets of well-known gates; such a universality theorem exists, for instance, for the pair consisting of the single qubit phase gate *U*θ mentioned above (for a suitable value of θ), together with the 2-qubit CNOT gate *W*CNOT.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] However, the universality theorem for the quantum case is somewhat weaker than the one for the classical case; it asserts only that any reversible *n*-qubit circuit can be *approximated* arbitrarily well by circuits assembled from these two elementary gates.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] Note that there are uncountably many possible single qubit phase gates, one for every possible angle θ, so they cannot all be represented by a finite circuit constructed from {*U*θ, *W*CNOT}.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] So far we have not shown how quantum circuits are used to perform computations.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] Since many important numerical problems reduce to computing a unitary transformation *U* on a finite-dimensional space (the celebrated discrete Fourier transform being a prime example), one might expect that some quantum circuit could be designed to carry out the transformation *U*.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] In principle, one needs only to prepare an *n* qubit state ψ as an appropriate superposition of computational basis states for the input and measure the output *U*ψ.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] This does not prevent quantum circuits for the discrete Fourier transform from being used as intermediate steps in other quantum circuits, but the use is more subtle.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] In fact quantum computations are *probabilistic*.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] We now provide a mathematical model for how quantum circuits can simulate *probabilistic* but classical computations.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] Consider an *r*-qubit circuit *U* with register space *H*QB(*r*).
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] The contents *x* = *x*1, ..., *x**m* of the classical input register are used to initialize the qubit register in some way.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] where there are *r*-*m* underbraced zeroed inputs.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] Nevertheless, this perfect initialization is completely unrealistic.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] Let us assume therefore that the initialization is a mixed state given by some density operator *S* which is near the idealized input in some appropriate metric, e.g.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] Similarly, the output register space is related to the qubit register, by a *Y* valued observable *A*.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] Note that observables in quantum mechanics are usually defined in terms of *projection valued measures* on **R**; if the variable happens to be discrete, the projection valued measure reduces to a family {Eλ} indexed on some parameter λ ranging over a countable set.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] on *Y* can be used to determine *F*(*x*) with an arbitrarily small probability of error by majority sampling, for a sufficiently large sample size.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] Specifically, take *k* independent samples from the probability distribution Pr on *Y* and choose a value on which more than half of the samples agree.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-circuit] This follows by applying the Chernoff bound.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-turing-machine] A **quantum Turing machine** (**QTM**) or **universal quantum computer** is an abstract machine used to model the effects of a quantum computer.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-turing-machine] It provides a simple model that captures all of the power of quantum computation—that is, any quantum algorithm can be expressed formally as a particular quantum Turing machine.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-turing-machine] However, the computationally equivalent quantum circuit is a more common model.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-turing-machine] Quantum Turing machines can be related to classical and probabilistic Turing machines in a framework based on transition matrices.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-turing-machine] That is, a matrix can be specified whose product with the matrix representing a classical or probabilistic machine provides the quantum probability matrix representing the quantum machine.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-turing-machine] A way of understanding the quantum Turing machine (QTM) is that it generalizes the classical Turing machine (TM) in the same way that the quantum finite automaton (QFA) generalizes the deterministic finite automaton (DFA).
[src:bqp-class/quantum-turing-machine] In essence, the internal states of a classical TM are replaced by pure or mixed states in a Hilbert space; the transition function is replaced by a collection of unitary matrices that map the Hilbert space to itself.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-turing-machine] That is, a classical Turing machine is described by a 7-tuple $M=\langle Q,\Gamma ,b,\Sigma ,\delta ,q_{0},F\rangle$ .
[src:bqp-class/quantum-turing-machine] See the formal definition of a Turing Machine for a more in-depth understanding of each of the elements in this tuple.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-turing-machine] The above is merely a sketch of a quantum Turing machine, rather than its formal definition, as it leaves vague several important details: for example, how often a measurement is performed; see for example, the difference between a measure-once and a measure-many QFA.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-turing-machine] This question of measurement affects the way in which writes to the output tape are defined.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-turing-machine] In 1980 and 1982, physicist Paul Benioff published articles that first described a quantum-mechanical model of Turing machines.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-turing-machine] A 1985 article written by Oxford University physicist David Deutsch further developed the idea of quantum computers by suggesting that quantum gates could function in a similar fashion to traditional digital computing binary logic gates.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-turing-machine] Iriyama, Ohya, and Volovich have developed a model of a *linear quantum Turing machine* (LQTM).
[src:bqp-class/quantum-turing-machine] This is a generalization of a classical QTM that has mixed states and that allows irreversible transition functions.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-turing-machine] These allow the representation of quantum measurements without classical outcomes.
[src:bqp-class/quantum-turing-machine] A *quantum Turing machine with postselection* was defined by Scott Aaronson, who showed that the class of polynomial time on such a machine (PostBQP) is equal to the classical complexity class PP.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] Shor proposed multiple similar algorithms for solving the factoring problem, the discrete logarithm problem, and the period-finding problem.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] "Shor's algorithm" usually refers to the factoring algorithm, but may refer to any of the three algorithms.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] The discrete logarithm algorithm and the factoring algorithm are instances of the period-finding algorithm, and all three are instances of the hidden subgroup problem.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] On a quantum computer, to factor an integer N , Shor's algorithm runs in polynomial time, meaning the time taken is polynomial in $\log N$ .
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] Shor's algorithm is asymptotically faster than the most scalable classical factoring algorithm, the general number field sieve, which works in sub-exponential time: $O\!\left(e^{1.9(\log N)^{1/3}(\log \log N)^{2/3}}\right)$ .
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] RSA can be broken if factoring large integers is computationally feasible.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] As far as is known, this is not possible using classical (non-quantum) computers; no classical algorithm is known that can factor integers in polynomial time.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] However, Shor's algorithm shows that factoring integers can be done with a polynomial complexity circuit on an ideal quantum computer.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] Thus, it might be feasible to defeat RSA by constructing a large enough quantum computer.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] This was a powerful motivator for the design and construction of quantum computers, and for the study of new quantum-computer algorithms.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] It has also facilitated research on new cryptosystems that are secure from quantum computers, collectively called post-quantum cryptography (PQC).
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] As of 2026, the high error rates of quantum computers and limited number of physical qubits available for quantum error correction, laboratory demonstrations of Shor's algorithm obtain correct results in only a fraction of attempts, and have only succeeded with small semiprimes.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] In 2001, Shor's algorithm was demonstrated by a group at IBM, who factored $15$ into $3\times 5$ , using an NMR implementation of a quantum computer with seven qubits.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] After IBM's implementation, two independent groups implemented Shor's algorithm using photonic qubits, emphasizing that multi-qubit entanglement was observed when running Shor's algorithm circuits.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] In 2012, the factorization of $15$ was performed with solid-state qubits.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] Later, in 2012, the factorization of $21$ was achieved.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] In 2016, the factorization of $15$ was performed again using trapped-ion qubits.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] However, none of these demonstrations fulfill the requirements of Shor’s algorithm: they compile the circuit using prior knowledge of the solution, and some have even oversimplified the algorithm in a way that makes it equivalent to coin flipping.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] The problem that we are trying to solve is: *given an odd composite number N , find its integer factors*.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] A quantum algorithm to solve the order-finding problem.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] A complete factoring algorithm is possible if we're able to efficiently factor arbitrary N into just two integers p and q greater than 1, since if either p or q are not prime, then the factoring algorithm can in turn be run on those until only primes remain.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] A basic observation is that, using Euclid's algorithm, we can always compute the GCD between two integers efficiently.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] In particular, this means we can check efficiently whether N is even, in which case 2 is trivially a factor.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] Let us thus assume that N is odd for the remainder of this discussion.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] Afterwards, we can use efficient classical algorithms to check whether N is a prime power.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] For prime powers, efficient classical factorization algorithms exist, hence the rest of the quantum algorithm may assume that N is not a prime power.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] If those easy cases do not produce a nontrivial factor of N , the algorithm proceeds to handle the remaining case.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] We pick a random integer $2\leq a<N{.}$ A possible nontrivial divisor of N can be found by computing $\gcd(a,N)$ , which can be done classically and efficiently using the Euclidean algorithm.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] If this produces a nontrivial factor (meaning $\gcd(a,N)\neq 1$ ), the algorithm is finished, and the other nontrivial factor is $N/\gcd(a,N)$ .
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] If a nontrivial factor was not identified, then this means that N and the choice of a are coprime, so a is contained in the multiplicative group of integers modulo N , having a multiplicative inverse modulo N .
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] and r is the smallest positive integer satisfying this congruence.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] It can be seen from the congruence that N divides $a^{r}-1$ , written $N\mid a^{r}-1$ .
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] This can be factored using difference of squares: $N\mid (a^{r/2}-1)(a^{r/2}+1).$ Since we have factored the expression in this way, the algorithm doesn't work for odd r (because $a^{r/2}$ must be an integer), meaning that the algorithm would have to restart with a new a .
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] Hereafter we can therefore assume that r is even.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] It cannot be the case that $N\mid a^{r/2}-1$ , since this would imply $a^{r/2}\equiv 1{\bmod {N}}$ , which would contradictorily imply that $r/2$ would be the order of a , which was already r .
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] At this point, it may or may not be the case that $N\mid a^{r/2}+1$ .
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] If N does not divide $a^{r/2}+1$ , then this means that we are able to find a nontrivial factor of N .
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] We compute $d=\gcd(N,a^{r/2}-1).$ If $d=1$ , then $N\mid a^{r/2}+1$ was true, and a nontrivial factor of N cannot be achieved from a , and the algorithm must restart with a new a .
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] Otherwise, we have found a nontrivial factor of N , with the other being $N/d$ , and the algorithm is finished.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] For this step, it is also equivalent to compute $\gcd(N,a^{r/2}+1)$ ; it will produce a nontrivial factor if $\gcd(N,a^{r/2}-1)$ is nontrivial, and will not if it's trivial (where $N\mid a^{r/2}+1$ ).
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] The algorithm restated shortly follows: let N be odd, and not a prime power.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] We want to output two nontrivial factors of N .
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] Compute $K=\gcd(a,N)$ , the greatest common divisor of a and N .
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] If $K\neq 1$ , then K is a nontrivial factor of N , with the other factor being $N/K$ , and we are done.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] Otherwise, use the quantum subroutine to find the order r of a .
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] If g is nontrivial, the other factor is $N/g$ , and we're done.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] It has been shown that this will be likely to succeed after a few runs.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] In practice, a single call to the quantum order-finding subroutine is enough to completely factor N with very high probability of success if one uses a more advanced reduction.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] The goal of the quantum subroutine of Shor's algorithm is, given coprime integers N and $1<a<N$ , to find the order r of a modulo N , the smallest positive integer r such that $a^{r}\equiv 1{\pmod {N}}$ .
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] To achieve this, Shor's algorithm uses a quantum circuit involving two registers.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] The second register uses n qubits, where n is the smallest integer such that $N\leq 2^{n}$ , i.e., $n=\left\lceil {\log _{2}N}\right\rceil$ .
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] The size of the first register determines how accurate of an approximation the circuit produces.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] It can be shown that using $2n$ qubits gives sufficient accuracy to find r .
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] The exact quantum circuit depends on the parameters a and N , which define the problem.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] The following description of the algorithm uses bra–ket notation to denote quantum states, and $\otimes$ to denote the tensor product.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] Use the continued fractions algorithm to extract the period r from the measurement outcomes obtained in the previous stage.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] This is a procedure to post-process (with a classical computer) the measurement data obtained from measuring the output quantum states, and retrieve the period.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] The connection with quantum phase estimation was not discussed in the original formulation of Shor's algorithm, but was later proposed by Alexei Kitaev.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] In other words, it sends each eigenstate $|\psi _{j}\rangle$ of U to a state containing information close to the associated eigenvalue.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] Implementing the circuit for quantum phase estimation with U requires being able to efficiently implement the gates $U^{2^{j}}$ .
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] This can be accomplished via modular exponentiation, which is the slowest part of the algorithm.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] The gate thus defined satisfies $U^{r}=I$ , which immediately implies that its eigenvalues are the r -th roots of unity $\omega _{r}^{k}=e^{2\pi ik/r}$ .
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] Using quantum phase estimation on an input state $|0\rangle ^{\otimes 2n}|\psi _{j}\rangle$ would then return the integer $2^{2n}j/r$ with high probability.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] This probability can be made arbitrarily close to 1 using extra qubits.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] Then, we apply the continued-fraction algorithm to find integers b and c , where $b/c$ gives the best fraction approximation for the approximation measured from the circuit, for $b,c<N$ and coprime b and c .
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] However, while b and c are coprime, it may be the case that j and r are not coprime.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] Because of that, b and c may have lost some factors that were in j and r .
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] This can be remedied by rerunning the quantum order-finding subroutine an arbitrary number of times, to produce a list of fraction approximations ${\frac {b_{1}}{c_{1}}},{\frac {b_{2}}{c_{2}}},\ldots ,{\frac {b_{s}}{c_{s}}},$ where s is the number of times the subroutine was run.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] Each $c_{k}$ will have different factors taken out of it because the circuit will (likely) have measured multiple different possible values of j .
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] To recover the actual r value, we can take the least common multiple of each $c_{k}$ : $\operatorname {lcm} (c_{1},c_{2},\ldots ,c_{s}).$ The least common multiple will be the order r of the original integer a with high probability.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] In practice, a single run of the quantum order-finding subroutine is in general enough if more advanced post-processing is used.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] Each $|\phi _{j}\rangle$ before measurement in Shor's algorithm represents a superposition of integers approximating $2^{2n}j/r$ .
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] Let $|k\rangle$ represent the most optimal integer in $|\phi _{j}\rangle$ .
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] As k is the optimal bitstring from phase estimation, $k/2^{2{n}}$ is accurate to $j/r$ by $2n$ bits.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] The runtime bottleneck of Shor's algorithm is quantum modular exponentiation, which is by far slower than the quantum Fourier transform and classical pre-/post-processing.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] There are several approaches to constructing and optimizing circuits for modular exponentiation.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] The simplest and (currently) most practical approach is to mimic conventional arithmetic circuits with reversible gates, starting with ripple-carry adders.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] Knowing the base and the modulus of exponentiation facilitates further optimizations.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] Reversible circuits typically use on the order of $n^{3}$ gates for n qubits.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] Alternative techniques asymptotically improve gate counts by using quantum Fourier transforms, but are not competitive with fewer than 600 qubits owing to high constants.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] Shor's algorithms for the discrete log and the order finding problems are instances of an algorithm solving the period finding problem.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] All three are instances of the hidden subgroup problem.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] Given a group G with order p and generator $g\in G$ , suppose we know that $x=g^{r}\in G$ , for some $r\in \mathbb {Z} _{p}$ , and we wish to compute r , which is the discrete logarithm: $r={\log _{g}}(x)$ .
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] Consider the abelian group $\mathbb {Z} _{p}\times \mathbb {Z} _{p}$ , where each factor corresponds to modular addition of values.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] This gives us an abelian hidden subgroup problem, where f corresponds to a group homomorphism.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] The kernel corresponds to the multiples of $(r,1)$ .
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] So, if we can find the kernel, we can find r .
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] A quantum algorithm for solving this problem exists.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] This algorithm is, like the factor-finding algorithm, due to Peter Shor and both are implemented by creating a superposition through using Hadamard gates, followed by implementing f as a quantum transform, followed finally by a quantum Fourier transform.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] The order-finding problem can also be viewed as a hidden subgroup problem.
[src:bqp-class/shor-s-algorithm] For any finite abelian group G , a quantum algorithm exists for solving the hidden subgroup for G in polynomial time.
